// AnimationLayer.tjs - Layer that performs animations

// Copyright (C) 2001-2008, W.Dee and contributors. Free to modify and distribute.





/*

-- Two Types of Animation ---------------------------------------------



　There are two ways to perform animations in KAG.

　One is cell-based animation using "cell images." In this case, 
various parts of the "cell image" are sequentially cut out and pasted 
onto a "base image."



　The other is clipping-based animation, which became available in 
KAG 3.05 beta 3. This method does not require a separate cell image.
　The image tag has four attributes: clipleft, cliptop, clipwidth, 
and clipheight. By (conceptually) changing these sequentially, you 
can display different parts of a large image one after another. 
This is suitable for cases where multiple frames are lined up 
horizontally in one image.



　The processing load for clipping-based animation is lighter. In 
demo scenes where you animate by redrawing the entire area of a layer, 
clipping-based animation is better.
　Conversely, for things like blinking or lip-syncing, cell-based 
animation is more flexible and easier to use.





-- How to Write Cell-Based Animations -----------------------------------



　First, to perform an animation, you need a "base image" and a 
"cell image." The base image is the background/foundation for the 
animation. The cell image contains the animation "parts." Parts of 
the cell image are copied and layered onto the base image.



　The base image is loaded using the [image] tag (the "base" here 
refers to the layer's initial state, not the KAG background layer "base"). 
The cell image is loaded using the [loadcell] tag within the 
animation definition file.



　The animation definition file is a text file with the same name 
as the base image but with an .asd extension.
　The animation definition file is written using KAG syntax, but 
the tag system is different from standard KAG.



　For simple animations that don't use animation segments, the 
LineBreak or PageBreak files in the KAG system folder are useful references.
　A sample using animation segments is currently located in the 
Kirikiri source at environ/win32/kag3/scenario/animtest.ks.



-- Segments -------------------------------------------------------------



　A segment is a mechanism to allow multiple animations (sharing 
the same base, cell, and asd file) to run simultaneously.
　Segments are numbered starting from 0 for each layer.
　Segment 0 is a special segment called the "default segment," 
which starts automatically when the image is loaded. LineBreak 
and PageBreak in the system folder only use this default segment. 
For simple animations, this is sufficient.



　If you want to handle lip-sync and blinking in a single image, 
you must use multiple segments. For example, blinking can run 
continuously in the default segment, while lip-sync is started 
or stopped via scenario control.



　Starting an animation for a specific segment is done using the 
[animstart] tag in a normal KAG scenario. [animstart] starts 
animation in any segment (other than the default segment).



　When the loop attribute of the [animstart] tag is true, the 
animation must be scripted to loop. It doesn't loop automatically; 
you must write the asd file so it jumps back.
　While failing to loop won't cause an error, the image might 
not be reproduced correctly when loading a saved game.
Also, when a save is loaded, animation restarts only if loop=true 
was specified, starting from the beginning of the label in the 
asd file specified in [animstart].



　When loop=false, the animation runs but must eventually stop 
using the [s] tag. Also, when stopped with [s], the image must 
return to the same state as the base image. Use this for 
one-shot animations.



　[animstop] stops an animation but does not wait for it to finish. 
In reality, the animation stops only after passing through a 
[@home] tag.



　[wa] waits for an animation in a specific segment to finish. 
It can also wait for the default segment. This is only effective 
when loop=false was specified in [animstart], or when the 
animation was stopped with [animstop]. In other cases, [wa] 
will wait forever.



　The only information stored in save files is which segment 
started from which label; the exact frame position is not recorded.
　Only animations that were looping will be resumed when 
loading a save.





-- How to Write Clipping-Based Animations ---------------------------



　Unlike cell-based animations, for clipping-based animations, 
you prepare a single image where each frame is lined up horizontally.
　For example, if you want to animate 8 frames on a 320x240 screen, 
prepare a 2560x240 image (2560 = 320 * 8).
　When loading the image, write the [image] tag so that the first 
frame is displayed.
　For example:



@image storage=anim page=fore layer=0 mode=rect clipleft=0 cliptop=0 clipwidth=320 clipheight=240



　In the .asd file, write descriptions to sequentially display 
each frame lined up horizontally. Since no cell image is used, 
there is no need for [loadcell].
　Example:



@wait time=80
@clip left=320 top=0
@wait time=80
@clip left=640 top=0
@wait time=80
@clip left=960 top=0
@wait time=80
@clip left=1280 top=0
@wait time=80
@clip left=1600 top=0
@wait time=80
@clip left=1920 top=0
@wait time=80
@clip left=2240 top=0
@wait time=80
@s



　As you might notice, they don't actually have to be horizontal.
　Vertical is fine, but when compressing with PNG, lining 
them up horizontally often yields a better compression ratio.



　For clipping-based animations, information on how the layer was 
animating is not stored in save files. Please invalidate the 
clipping animation information (e.g., by loading a different 
image to that layer) before passing the next "Save-able label."





-- Description of tags in asd files ---------------------------------------





■ loadcell



・Attributes



  storage (optional)        Specifies the cell image filename to load.



・Description



　This tag is used only for cell-based animations.
　The [loadcell] tag loads the animation cell image. Since 
animation cannot be performed without loading a cell image, 
always include this at the beginning of the .asd file.
If the storage attribute is omitted, an image with "_a" 
appended to the base image's filename will be loaded.
　Writing it at the start of the .asd file is sufficient; 
you don't need to write it after every segment start label.





■ loop



・Attributes



  (none)



・Description



　This tag is used only for cell-based animations.
　The [loop] tag declares that the data is intended to loop.
　Declaring this does not mean the data loops automatically. 
Please write your script so it loops.
　Place this tag near the entry label of segments that loop. 
For the default segment, placing it after [loadcell] is fine.



■ copy



・Attributes



  dx                        Destination x coordinate
  dy                        Destination y coordinate
  sx                        Source x coordinate
  sy                        Source y coordinate
  sw                        Width
  sh                        Height



・Description



　This tag is used only for cell-based animations.
　Copies from the cell image to the base image.



■ wait



・Attributes



  time                      Wait time (ms)



・Description



　Waits for the specified time.
　Usually, this is used in a cycle with the [copy] tag.



■ jump, if/endif, eval, iscript/endscript



　Same as KAG scenarios.
　However, since multiple segments can run in parallel, 
be careful not to overlap variables if you are manipulating them.



■ s



・Attributes



  (none)



・Description



　Stops execution, just like in normal KAG.
　If the animation does not loop, stop it with this tag 
instead of using the [loop] tag.
　If you don't want to animate immediately when the image 
is loaded, write [s] immediately after [loadcell].







■ home



・Attributes



  (none)



・Description



　This tag is used only for cell-based animations.
　This is the point where execution stops when [animstop] 
is called. You cannot stop via [animstop] without this. 
When using [animstop], ensure at least one [home] tag is 
placed within the loop.







■ clip



・Attributes



  left                      Left position for clipping
  top                       Top position for clipping



　This tag is used only for clipping-based animations.
　Specifies the clipping position, identical to the 
clipleft and cliptop attributes in the [image] tag.
　Since the width and height of the clipping cannot 
be changed, the size specified in the [image] tag remains fixed.



*/





class AnimationConductor extends BaseConductor
{
	var owner;
	var number; // Number of this conductor
	var looping = false;
	var startLabel = "";
	var stopping = false; // Whether it is waiting to stop
	var running = false; // Whether it is running

	function AnimationConductor(owner)
	{
		super.BaseConductor(); // Call superclass constructor
		ignoreCR = true; // Ignore CR
		debugLevel = tkdlNone;
//		debugLevel = tkdlVerbose;
		this.owner = owner;
	}

	function finalize()
	{
		owner = void; // Clear reference to owner
		super.finalize(...);
	}

	function onStop()
	{
		// Stop execution
		var elm = %[];
		elm.context = this;
		owner.s(elm); // Call 's' tag
	}

	function onTag(obj)
	{
		// When a tag is executed
		var func = owner[obj.tagname];
		if(func == void)
		{
			dm(Storages.extractFileName(curStorage) + " : Unknown tag : " + obj.tagname);
			return 0;
		}
		obj.context = this;
		return func(obj);
	}

	function onScript(script, scriptname, lineofs)
	{
		// When iscript is executed
		try
		{
			Scripts.exec(script, scriptname, lineofs);
		}
		catch(e)
		{
			throw new Exception(scriptname + " line " + lineofs + ": "
				"Error occurred in iscript block."
				"\n( See console for details )\n" + e.message);
		}
		return true;
	}

	function assign(src)
	{
		// Copy state from src to this object
		super.assign(src);
		looping = src.looping;
		startLabel = src.startLabel;
		stopping = src.stopping;
		running = src.running;
	}
}





class AnimationLayer extends AffineLayer
{
	var Anim_cellLayer; // Cell layer
	var Anim_segments = []; // Conductors for each segment
	var Anim_storageName; // Animation data filename
	var Anim_loadParams = void; // Parameters specified during loading
	var Anim_partialImageInfo = void; // Parameters for partial image loading
	var Anim_interrupted = false; // Whether it is interrupted

	var Anim_defaultFontInfo = %[];
	var Anim_seLabelWait = void; // Waiting for SELabel

	function AnimationLayer(win, par)
	{
		// AnimationLayer constructor
		super.AffineLayer(...); // Call superclass constructor
		initAnim();
	}

	function finalize()
	{
		if (Anim_seLabelWait !== void && isvalid window)
			window.removeHook("onSELabel", this.onSELabel);
		termAnim();
		super.finalize(...);
	}

	function clearImage(process = true)
	{
		// Make it invisible (if possible) and clear the layer
		// Override if necessary
		if(process)
		{
			visible = false;
			setSize(32, 32);
			setImageSize(32, 32);
			face = dfAlpha;
			fillRect(0, 0, 32, 32, 0);
			type = ltOpaque;
			face = dfAuto;
		}
	}

	function freeImage()
	{
		// Free image
		clearAnim();
		clearImage();
		clearClipImage();
		Anim_loadParams = void;
		Anim_partialImageInfo = void;
	}

	function initAnim() {
		if (typeof this.Anim_segments == "undefined") with (this) {
			.Anim_segments = [];
			.Anim_defaultFontInfo = %[];
			.Anim_cellLayer = .Anim_storageName = .Anim_loadParams = .Anim_partialImageInfo = void;
			.Anim_interrupted = false;
		}
		Anim_defaultFontInfo.face = font.face; // Default font
		Anim_defaultFontInfo.height = font.height; // Default font size

		Anim_segments[0] = new AnimationConductor(this); // Default conductor
		Anim_segments[0].number = 0;
	}

	function termAnim() {
		clearAnim(); // Clear animation info
		invalidate Anim_segments[0]; // Invalidate default conductor
		Anim_loadParams = void;
		Anim_partialImageInfo = void;
	}

	function clearAnim()
	{
		// Clear animation info
		// Clear animation segments
		// Remove each segment (except default)
		for(var i = Anim_segments.count -1; i>=1; i--)
		{
			var seg = Anim_segments[i];
			invalidate Anim_segments[i] if seg !== void;
		}
		Anim_segments.count = 1;

		// Stop default segment
		Anim_segments[0].stop();

		// Destroy animation cell layer
		invalidate Anim_cellLayer if Anim_cellLayer !== void;
		Anim_cellLayer = void;
	}

	function loadAnimInfo(segment, label)
	{
		// Load animation info into specified segment and start execution
		// segment = segment index, label = start label (empty string for beginning)
		// Loads the file specified in Anim_storageName
		if(Anim_storageName == '')
			throw new Exception(
				(Anim_loadParams !== void ? "For " + Anim_loadParams.storage + ": " : "") +
				"Animation information not found");

		var seg;
		if(Anim_segments[segment] === void)
		{
			Anim_segments[segment] = seg = new AnimationConductor(this);
			seg.number = segment;
				// Create conductor for new segment
		}
		else
		{
			// Stop segment
			(seg = Anim_segments[segment]).stop();
		}

		seg.startLabel = label;
		seg.stopping = false;
		seg.running = true;
		seg.clearCallStack();
		seg.interrupted = Anim_interrupted;
		seg.loadScenario(Anim_storageName);
		if(label != '') seg.goToLabel(label);
		seg.startProcess(true);
	}

	function startAnim(elm)
	{
		// Start animation according to elm
		loadAnimInfo(+elm.seg, elm.target);
	}

	function stopAnim(segment)
	{
		// Stop animation in segment
		var seg = Anim_segments[segment];
		if(seg === void) return; // Cannot stop
		seg.stopping = true;
	}

	function canWaitAnimStop(segment)
	{
		// Whether we can wait for segment's animation to end
		var seg = Anim_segments[segment];
		if(seg === void) return false; // Cannot wait
		if(!seg.running) return false; // Cannot wait as it's not running
		if(seg.looping && !seg.stopping) return false; // Cannot wait if looping and not stopping
		return true;
	}

	function superLoadImages() { return super.loadImages(...); }

	function loadImages(elm)
	{
		// loadImages override
		// elm is the load information
		if(elm === void)
		{
			freeImage();
			return;
		}

		// Check if asd file exists
		Anim_storageName =
			Storages.getPlacedPath(
				Storages.chopStorageExt(elm.storage) + ".asd");

		// If the start of asd is ;!, overwrite elm
		if(Anim_storageName != '') {
			var tmp = [];
			var exp = tmp.load(Anim_storageName)[0];
			if (exp !== void && exp.charAt(0) == ';' && exp.charAt(1) == '!') {
				tmp = exp.substr(2).split(" ",, true);
				for (var i = 0; i < tmp.count; i++)
					tmp[i] = "." + tmp[i] + (tmp[i].indexOf("=") < 0 ? "=true" : "");
				exp = "with (this) " + tmp.join(",") + ";";
				(function(e) { e!; } incontextof elm)(exp);
			}
		}

		Anim_loadParams = %[];
		(Dictionary.assign incontextof Anim_loadParams)(elm);
			// Save parameters

		// Clear animation info
		clearAnim();

		// Clear partial image info
		Anim_partialImageInfo = void;

		if (elm.color !== void) {
			var opac = (elm.coloropacity !== void) ? +elm.coloropacity : 255;
			// Fill color
			setSize(+elm.width, +elm.height);
			fillRect(0, 0, +elm.width, +elm.height, (opac << 24) | +elm.color);
		} else {
			// Load image
			if (elm.storage !== void) {
				var taginfo = superLoadImages(elm.storage, elm.key, elm);
				// Adopt image tag info as default values
				if(taginfo)	{
					(Dictionary.assign incontextof taginfo)(elm, false);
					elm = taginfo;
				}
			}
		}

		// Flip
		var ud, lr;
		if(elm.flipud !== void && +elm.flipud)
		{
			// Vertical flip
			flipUD();
			ud = true;
		}
		else
		{
			ud = false;
		}

		if(elm.fliplr !== void && +elm.fliplr)
		{
			// Horizontal flip
			flipLR();
			lr = true;
		}
		else
		{
			lr = false;
		}

		// Clipping
		if(elm.clipleft !== void)
		{
			// Clipping specified
			width = +elm.clipwidth;
			height = +elm.clipheight;
			var cl = elm.clipleft;
			if(lr) cl = imageWidth - cl - width;
			var ct = elm.cliptop;
			if(ud) ct = imageHeight - ct - height;
			imageLeft = -cl;
			imageTop = -ct;
		}
		else
		{
			setSizeToImageSize();
		}

		// Layer mode
		{
			// affinelayer uses void to select appropriate initial mode
			//var mode = ltAlpha;
			var mode;

			if(elm.mode !== void)
			{
				var layertypeinfo = imageTagLayerType[elm.mode];
				if(layertypeinfo !== void)
					mode = layertypeinfo.type;
			}

			type = mode;
		}

		// Color correction
		applyColorCorrection(this, elm);

		// Visibility, position, opacity, index
		if ( elm !== void && elm.pos !== void ) {
			// Determine position based on pos
			if (window.scPositionX[elm.pos] !== void) {
				left= window.scPositionX[elm.pos] - width \ 2;
			} else {
				left= +elm.pos - width \ 2;
			}
			top = window.scHeight - height + (elm.yoff !== void ? +elm.yoff : 0);
		}
		else
		{
			if(elm.left !== void) left = +elm.left;
			if(elm.top !== void) top = +elm.top;
		}
		if(elm.visible !== void) visible = +elm.visible;
		if(elm.opacity !== void) opacity = +elm.opacity;
		absolute = +elm.index if elm.index !== void;

		// Load animation info if present
		if(Anim_storageName != '')
		{
			// Animation info found!
			// Load animation info into default conductor
			loadAnimInfo(0, ''); // And start animation (if it can start)
		}
	}

	function addPartialImageInfo(elm)
	{
		// Add elm to partialImageInfo
		if(Anim_partialImageInfo === void)
			Anim_partialImageInfo = [];
		var info = %[];
		(Dictionary.assign incontextof info)(elm);
		Anim_partialImageInfo.add(info);
	}

	function loadPartialImage(elm)
	{
		// Perform partial additional image loading
		// This loading method follows the layer's own 
		// color correction and flip settings.
		// (Therefore, the pimage tag itself does not have 
		// color correction or flip attributes.)
		// pimage tags are not suitable for sequential loading 
		// of partial images with timing offsets for animation.
		// (Use the animation feature for such cases.)
		 if(elm.tagname === void) elm.tagname = "pimage";

		// Determine color key
		var key;
		if(elm.key !== void)
		{
			// key specified
			key = elm.key;
		}
		else
		{
			// key not specified
			if(Anim_loadParams !== void)
				key = Anim_loadParams.key; // Use key from loadParams
			else
				key = void;
		}

		// Get temporary layer
		var temp = window.temporaryLayer;

		// Load image into temporary layer
		var taginfo = temp.loadImages(elm.storage, key);

		// Adopt image tag info as default values
		if(taginfo)
		{
			(Dictionary.assign incontextof taginfo)(elm, false);
			elm = taginfo;
		}

		// Layer mode
		{
			var mode = ltAlpha;

			if(elm.mode !== void)
			{
				var layertypeinfo = imageTagLayerType[elm.mode];
				if(layertypeinfo !== void)
					mode = layertypeinfo.type;
			}

			temp.type = mode;
		}

		// Image adjustment
		var lr = false, ud = false;
		if(Anim_loadParams !== void)
		{
			// Apply color correction to temp layer
			applyColorCorrection(temp, Anim_loadParams);

			// Flip
			if(Anim_loadParams.flipud !== void && +Anim_loadParams.flipud)
			{
				// Vertical flip
				temp.flipUD();
				ud = true;
			}

			if(Anim_loadParams.fliplr !== void && +Anim_loadParams.fliplr)
			{
				// Horizontal flip
				temp.flipLR();
				lr = true;
			}
		}

		var dx = +elm.dx;
		var dy = +elm.dy;
		var sx = +elm.sx;
		var sy = +elm.sy;
		var sw = elm.sw === void ? temp.imageWidth : +elm.sw;
		var sh = elm.sh === void ? temp.imageHeight : +elm.sh;
		if(ud)
		{
			// Vertical flip adjustment
			dy = imageHeight - dy - sh;
			sy = temp.imageHeight - sy - sh;
		}
		if(lr)
		{
			// Horizontal flip adjustment
			dx = imageWidth - dx - sw;
			sx = temp.imageWidth - sx - sw;
		}

		if(elm.mode == 'copy' || elm.mode == 'opaque')
		{
			// Copy
			face = dfAlpha;
			copyRect(dx, dy, temp, sx, sy, sw, sh);
		}
		else
		{
			// Overlay
			var opa = elm.opacity === void ? 255 : +elm.opacity;

			switch(elm.mode)
			{
			case '': // default
			case 'pile':
			case 'alpha':
				holdAlpha = false;
				face = dfAlpha;
				break;
			case 'addalpha':
				holdAlpha = false;
				face = dfAddAlpha;
				break;
			default:
				holdAlpha = true;
				face = dfOpaque;
				break;
			}
			operateRect(dx, dy, temp, sx, sy, sw, sh, omAuto, opa);

			face = dfAuto;
		}

		// Add info to Anim_partialImageInfo
		addPartialImageInfo(elm);

		return 0;
	}

	function drawReconstructibleText(elm)
	{
		 // Draw text in a format that can be reconstructed (on load)
		 // x, y = coordinates
		 // text = string to draw
		 // face = font, defaults to Anim_defaultFontInfo.face
		 // size = font size, defaults to Anim_defaultFontInfo.height
		 // color = color (default = 0xffffff)
		 // italic = whether it's italic (default = false)
		 // shadow = whether it has a shadow (default = true)
		 // edge = whether it has an edge (default = false)
		 // shadowcolor = shadow color (default = 0)
		 // edgecolor = edge color (default = 0)
		 // bold = whether it's bold (default = false)
		 // vertical = whether it's vertical (default = false)
		 // antialiased = whether to use anti-aliasing (default = true)
		 // angle = draw angle (default = 2700 if vertical, else 0)
		 if(elm.tagname === void) elm.tagname = "ptext";

		var vertical = elm.vertical === void ? false : +elm.vertical;

		with(font)
		{
			var face = elm.face === void ? Anim_defaultFontInfo.face : elm.face;
			if(vertical) face = '@' + face;
			.face = face;
			.height = elm.size === void ? Anim_defaultFontInfo.height : +elm.size;
			.angle = elm.angle === void ? vertical ? 2700:0 : +elm.angle;
			.italic = elm.italic === void ? false : +elm.italic;
			.bold = elm.bold === void ? false: +elm.bold;
		}

		var edge = elm.edge === void ? false : +elm.edge;
		var shadow = elm.shadow === void ? true : +elm.shadow;
		var color = elm.color === void ? 0xffffff : +elm.color;
		var antialiased = elm.antialiased === void ? true : +elm.antialiased;

		face = dfAuto;

		var x = +elm.x;
		var y = +elm.y;

		if(edge)
		{
			var bcolor = elm.edgecolor === void ? 0 : +elm.edgecolor;
			drawText(x, y, elm.text, color, 255, antialiased, 512, bcolor, 1, 0, 0);
		}
		else if(shadow)
		{
			var bcolor = elm.shadowcolor === void ? 0 : +elm.shadowcolor;
			drawText(x, y, elm.text, color, 255, antialiased, 255, bcolor, 0, 2, 2);
		}
		else
		{
			drawText(x, y, elm.text, color, 255, antialiased); // text
		}

		// Add info to Anim_partialImageInfo
		addPartialImageInfo(elm);

		return 0;
	}

	function applyColorCorrection(layer, param)
	{
		if (param === void || (typeof layer.isBitmap == "Object" && !layer.isBitmap())) return;
		// Apply color correction to layer
		var orgface = layer.face;
		var orgholdlpha = layer.holdAlpha;
		layer.face = dfAuto;
		if(param.grayscale !== void && +param.grayscale)
		{
			layer.doGrayScale();
		}
		if (param.rgamma !== void || param.rfloor !== void || param.rceil !== void ||
			param.ggamma !== void || param.gfloor !== void || param.gceil !== void ||
			param.bgamma !== void || param.bfloor !== void || param.bceil !== void) {
			layer.adjustGamma(
				param.rgamma, param.rfloor, param.rceil,
				param.ggamma, param.gfloor, param.gceil,
